1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 {Black now has a major fork the road.} (4.
O-O {leads to the main lines of the Berlin.} Nxe4 5. d4 (5. Re1 Nd6 6. Nxe5 Be7
) 5... Nd6 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8) 4... Bc5 (4... d6 5. Nbd2 g6
6. c3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. d4 {This move is slightly premature, as White's center
now ends up under serious pressure.} (8. Re1 {and playing for d4 at a later
time is more standard.}) 8... exd4 9. cxd4 {[%csl Gc7,Gd4,Gd6,Ge4][%cal Gd4e4,
Gd2e4,Gf6e4,Gg7d4] The bishop on g7 is quite nice, as it safeguards the king
and puts pressure on the center from a safe square.} Bd7 (9... Bg4 {[%csl Rd4,
Re4,Rf3][%cal Gg4d1] is my preferred move.} 10. Qc2 (10. d5 Nd4) (10. h3 Bxf3
11. Nxf3 (11. Qxf3 Nxd4) 11... Nxe4) 10... Nb4 11. Qb3 c5 $1 {with excellent
play.}) 10. Re1 Re8 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Gc1g5,Ge8e4,Gf6e4]} 11. h3 a5 12. a3 Re7 (
12... a4 {is more natural, with the idea that} 13. Bxa4 {runs into} Nxd4 $1 {
[%csl Ra4][%cal Gd7a4,Gd4f3]}) 13. Bd3 Nh5 {[%cal Gg7d4]} 14. d5 {[%csl Ge5]
[%cal Gg7b2] Black to Move} Nb8 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c5]} (14... Ne5 15. Nxe5 Rxe5 (
15... Bxe5 16. Nf3 Bg7 17. Bg5) 16. Nf3 Re8 17. Bg5) 15. Nf1 Nf6 (15... Na6)
16. Ng3 Na6 17. Bxa6 Rxa6 18. Bf4 h6 19. Rc1 a4 20. Rc4 Kh7 21. Qd2 Be8 22. Be3
c6 23. dxc6 Bxc6 24. Bd4 Ra8 25. Bc3 d5 26. Rd4 Qe8 27. e5 Ne4 28. Nxe4 dxe4
29. Rexe4 Bxe4 30. Rxe4 Rd7 31. Qc2 Rd5 32. e6 Rc8 33. exf7 Qxf7 34. Qe2 Rc7
35. Bxg7 Qxg7 36. Rxa4 Rc1+ 37. Kh2 Qc7+ 38. g3 Rc2 39. Qe3 Qc5 40. Nd4 Rxb2
41. Rc4 Re5 42. Qc3 Rxf2+ 43. Kg1 Qf8 44. Rc7+ Rf7 45. Qf3 Ree7 46. Ne6 Qe8 47.
Qe4 Rxe6 {0-1 (47) Christiansen, L (2559) -Goldin,A (2609) Qingdao 2002}) 5. c3
O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Nbd2 Ne7 8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4 Bb6 10. Re1 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. a4
(12. Qb3 Nc6 13. d5 {[%csl Re4,Re5][%cal Ge4d5,Gb6c7,Gb6f2] Black is usually
happy to see d5, as it opens up the bishop and keeps White from executing e5
ideas.} Nb8 14. Bf1 Nbd7 15. Qc2 Re8 16. b3 Bg6 {[%csl Rd5,Re4]} 17. Bb2 Nxd5
18. Rad1 N5f6 19. Qc3 Qe7 20. e5 dxe5 21. Nc4 Ne4 22. Rxe4 Bxe4 23. Nfxe5 Nxe5
24. Nxe5 Qf6 25. Qg3 Rad8 26. Re1 Rd2 {0-1 (26) Nepomniachtchi,I (2757)
-Grischuk,A (2766) chess.com INT 2018}) 12... a6 13. Bf1 Nc6 14. a5 Ba7 (14...
Nxa5 15. d5 {[%csl Ra5]}) (14... Bxa5 15. g4 Bg6 16. d5 Bxd2 17. Nxd2 {[%csl
Rg6][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5]}) (14... Bxf3 15. Nxf3 Bxa5 16. d5 Bxe1 17. dxc6 Bb4 18.
cxb7 Rb8 19. Bxa6) 15. Ra4 Re8 (15... h6 16. Qc2 Re8 17. Bd3 Bg6 18. b3 Qd7 19.
Bb2 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4][%cal Gb2d4,Ga4e4] Black to Move} Nh5 (19... d5 {was
probably the best try.} 20. e5 Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Nh5 (21... Nh7 {[%cal Ga7d4,Gb2d4]
}) 22. Qe3) 20. d5 {[%cal Gb2g7] Now that d5 opens up the bishop on b2, it is
quite a powerful idea.} Ne5 21. Nxe5 dxe5 {[%csl Rc7,Ge4,Re5,Rg6][%cal Gg6e4]}
22. Nf3 Nf4 23. Nxe5 Qd6 24. Ng4 Nxd5 25. Rd1 Nf4 26. Qc3 Ne6 27. Bc2 Qc5 28.
Rc4 Qg5 29. Rd5 Qh4 30. Kh2 c6 31. g3 Qe7 32. Nxh6+ Kh7 33. Nf5 cxd5 34. exd5
Qf6 35. Rh4+ Kg8 36. Nh6+ Kf8 37. Ba3+ Nc5 38. Bxc5+ Bxc5 39. Qxc5+ Qe7 40. Nf5
{Caruana-Kramnik 1-0.}) 16. Qb3 Qd7 17. d5 {[%cal Ga7f2]} Ne7 18. Rb4 b5 (18...
Bc5 19. Rxb7 Qc8 {[%csl Rb7]}) 19. axb6 Bxb6 20. Ra4 Reb8 (20... Rab8 {[%cal
Ge8e4] was more accurate.} 21. Qc2 c6 22. dxc6 Nxc6) 21. Qa2 {Black to Move} c6
22. dxc6 Nxc6 23. Bxa6 {Black to Move} (23. b4 {was preferable.}) 23... Nb4 $1
24. Rxb4 Bxf2+ 25. Kxf2 Rxb4 {[%csl Ra6,Rc1,Rd2,Rf2][%cal Gc1f4]} 26. Nc4 Qa7+
27. Re3 Qxa6 28. Ra3 Ra4 29. Nfd2 Bg6 30. Rxa4 Qxa4 31. Qxa4 Rxa4 32. b3 Ra2
33. Ke3 d5 34. exd5 Nxd5+ 35. Kd4 Nf4 36. Bb2 Ra8 37. Nd6 Ne6+ 38. Kc4 Ra6 39.
Be5 f6 40. Bg3 Kf8 41. b4 Ke7 42. Kd5 Nc7+ 43. Kc5 Ne6+ 44. Kd5 Nc7+ 45. Kc5
Kd7 46. N2c4 Rc6+ 47. Kd4 Ne6+ 48. Kc3 Nc7 49. b5 Rc5 50. b6 Na6 51. b7 Rg5 52.
Bf4 Rxg2 53. Nd2 Kc6 54. Nf3 Rc2+ 55. Kb3 Rf2 56. Nd4+ Kd5 57. Be3 Rh2 58. N6b5
Rxh3 59. Ka4 Nc5+ {0-1 (59) Najer,E (2670)-Potkin,V (2597) Moscow RUS 2018} *

