1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 (3... d6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7 {is generally
considered a worse version for Black, mainly because there is no option of b5.}
) 4. Ba4 Nf6 (4... d6 5. O-O (5. Bxc6+ bxc6 6. d4 {also leads to the same
structure, although Black also has the option of f6.} exd4) 5... Bd7 6. d4 Nxd4
{Not the only line by any means, but it leads to the purest form of the pawn
structure.} 7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. Nxd4 exd4 9. Qxd4 {[%csl Gb7,Gc7,Gd6,Ge4] This
structure is considered to be extremely solid, but also quite passive for
Black. It is important to either apply pressure to e4 or get in the f5 break.
Piece trades are also generally favorable.} Nf6 (9... Ne7 {is another common
setup. It allows a strong knight on d5, but it also allows for easier
counterplay with f5.} 10. Nc3 Nc6 11. Qd3 Be7 12. Nd5 {[%csl Gd5]} O-O 13. b3
Rae8 14. Bb2 Bd8 15. f4 f5 16. exf5 (16. e5 {is perhaps more testing, but
Black seems to hold the position together with} Re6 (16... dxe5 17. Nf6+))
16... Qxf5 17. Qc4 Qf7 18. Qc3 {Black to move} Nb8 $1 (18... Nb4 $5 {
Computerish move.} 19. Qxb4 (19. Nxb4 Bf6 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gf6b2]}) 19... Qxd5
20. Rad1 Qc6) (18... Bf6 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 20. Qc4+ (20. Qxf6 gxf6) 20... Qf7) (
18... Ne7 19. Nxc7) 19. Rf3 Nd7 20. Rg3 (20. Nxc7 Bf6) 20... Nf6 21. Rd1 c6 (
21... Nh5 22. Rh3 Re5 23. fxe5 Qf2+ 24. Kh1 Qf1+) 22. Nxf6+ Bxf6 23. Qxf6 Qxf6
{1/2-1/2 (23) Almasi,Z (2719)-Sokolov,I (2643) Nakhchivan 2011}) 10. Nc3 Be7
11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 c6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gc3d5]} 13. Rad1 Rad8 14. Rfe1 Rfe8 15.
Ne2 {[%csl Rf6] Black to Move} Nh5 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gg7g6,Gh5g7]} (15... d5 16. e5
Qf5 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gf6b2]} (16... Ne4 17. e6) 17. Qd3 Qxd3 18. cxd3 Nd7) 16. Qd3
Bf6 17. Bc1 g6 18. Qf3 Qe7 19. Ba3 Qxe4 20. Qxe4 Rxe4 21. Kf1 d5 {Black is up
a clear pawn now, but failed to convert his advantage.} 22. Nc1 Nf4 23. Bc5
Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Ne6 25. Bb6 Rc8 26. Nd3 c5 27. c4 dxc4 28. bxc4 Kf8 29. Rb1 Ke8
30. Ba7 Rc7 31. Bb6 Rc6 32. Ba7 Rc7 33. Bb6 Rd7 34. Nxc5 Nxc5 35. Bxc5 Kd8 36.
Ke2 Kc7 37. Rd1 Rxd1 38. Kxd1 Kc6 39. Be3 Be7 40. Kc2 f5 {1/2-1/2 (40) Salgado
Lopez,I (2627)-Demchenko,A (2645) Linares ESP 2017}) 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 d6 7.
Bxc6+ bxc6 8. d4 exd4 9. Nxd4 {[%csl Gc6,Gc7,Gd6,Ge4] This structure has
similar properties, but the doubled pawns make it slightly different. The pawn
push e5 is more of a positional threat, since taking on e5 leaves you with a
poor pawn structure on the queenside. On the other hand, Black can make use of
the b-file, and can also play c5 without weakening d6 too much.} Bd7 10. Qf3
O-O 11. Nc3 (11. e5 dxe5 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. Qxc6 Qd6 {and Black's development
lead compensates for the subpar pawns.}) 11... Re8 12. h3 {[%csl Rd7,Rd8,Re7,
Rf6]} h6 (12... c5 {[%cal Gc3d5]} 13. Nf5 Bxf5 14. exf5 (14. Qxf5 Nd7 15. Nd5)
14... d5 15. Bg5 c6 16. Re2) 13. Bd2 (13. Bf4 c5 (13... Nh7 14. e5 d5) 14. Nf5
(14. Nde2 Bc6 15. Ng3 Nd7 16. Nf5 Bf6) 14... Bxf5 15. exf5 d5) 13... Nh7 14.
Rad1 Bf6 15. Bf4 {Black to Play} Qb8 (15... Ng5 16. Bxg5 Bxg5 17. e5) (15...
Nf8 16. Bg3) 16. Nb3 Ng5 17. Qd3 Bxc3 (17... Ne6) 18. bxc3 Ne6 19. Be3 a5 20.
a4 (20. e5 {going after the dark squares looked quite strong.}) 20... c5 21.
Ra1 Bc6 {[%csl Ra4,Rb3,Gc6,Re4][%cal Gc6a4,Gc6e4] and now Black has an idea
position for this structure.} 22. c4 Qd8 23. Bd2 Qd7 24. Nxa5 Bxa4 25. Bc3 Ra6
26. Nb3 Rea8 27. Rab1 Qe7 28. Re3 Nf4 29. Qd2 Ng6 30. Bb2 Be8 31. Rg3 Qxe4 32.
Re1 Qf5 33. Qc3 f6 34. Rf3 Qg5 35. Rg3 Qf5 36. Rf3 Qg5 37. Rg3 {Hamdouchi -
Adams 1/2-1/2, 2004 Tripoli.} 1/2-1/2

