1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. O-O {This is most flexible, but
also gives Black many options.} (5. d4 {is the old move, but it allows Black
to have a nice version of the endgame after} exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 Bd7 {
and 0-0-0}) (5. Nc3 {is an interesting option that will often transpose, but
it makes Nxd4 options less desireable due to the king still being on e1.} f6 6.
d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 c5 8. Nde2 Qxd1+ 9. Nxd1) 7... Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Be3
O-O-O 10. O-O-O Ne7 {is a direct transposition.} 11. Nb3 b6 12. f4 Ng6 13. a3
c5 14. Rhf1 Bd6 15. Nd2 Rhe8 16. Nc4 Bf8 17. f5 Nh8 18. a4 Nf7 19. Bf4 b5 20.
axb5 axb5 21. Nd2 Bc6 22. Rde1 Nd6 23. Bxd6 Bxd6 24. g3 Be5 25. Nd1 Kb7 26. Nf3
Bd6 27. Nf2 Ra8 28. Kd2 Ra2 29. Ra1 Rxa1 30. Rxa1 Bxe4 31. Nxe4 Rxe4 32. Kd3
Rb4 33. Kc3 Kc6 34. Rd1 g5 35. fxg6 hxg6 36. b3 g5 37. Rf1 g4 38. Nd2 Rd4 39.
Nb1 Be5 40. Rf5 Rd8+ 41. Rxe5 b4+ 42. Kb2 fxe5 {0-1 (42) Adhiban,B (2567)
-Nakamura,H (2772) Tromso NOR 2013}) 5... f6 {This is the simplest way to
defend the pawn, and doesn't carry a huge risk as White has no light-squared
bishop.} (5... Qf6 {looks odd, but the idea is to defend the pawn without
walking into Na3-c4.} 6. d4 exd4 7. Bg5 Qd6 {Black "loses" a tempo, but the
bishop on g5 is misplaced.} 8. Nxd4 Ne7 9. Nc3 Bd7 {and positions are similar
to our main line.} 10. Nb3 Qxd1 11. Raxd1 b6 12. Rd2 O-O-O 13. Rfd1 f6 14. Be3
Ng6 15. Nc1 Bb4 16. N1e2 Ne5 17. b3 Be6 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 20. h3 c5
21. Nd5 a5 22. c4 a4 23. Nxb4 cxb4 24. Nd4 Bd7 25. Kf1 c5 26. Nc2 Nc6 27. Ke1
Na5 28. Nxb4 Be6 29. Kd2 axb3 30. axb3 Bxc4 31. Nc6+ Nxc6 32. bxc4 Kd7 33. Kc3
Ne7 34. Bf4 Kc6 35. f3 b5 36. cxb5+ Kxb5 37. Bd6 Ng6 38. g3 Kc6 39. Bb8 Nf8 40.
Kc4 Nd7 41. Bf4 g5 42. Be3 Ne5+ 43. Kc3 Nxf3 44. Kc4 Ne5+ 45. Kc3 Kb5 46. Bf2
Nc4 47. Bg1 h5 48. Bf2 Ne5 49. Be3 Nf7 50. Bd2 Nd6 51. Kd3 Nc4 52. Bc3 Ne5+ 53.
Kc2 Kc4 54. Ba1 Kb5 55. Kd2 c4 56. Ke3 Kc5 57. Bd4+ Kb4 58. Ke2 c3 59. Kd1 Kc4
60. Bb6 Kd3 61. Bd8 Nd7 62. h4 gxh4 63. gxh4 c2+ 64. Kc1 Nc5 {0-1 (64) Duda,J 
(2737)-Karjakin,S (2773) chess.com INT 2018}) (5... Bg4 {one of the old main
lines, trying to maintain a pin on the knight using tactics.} 6. h3 h5 (6...
Bh5 7. g4 Bg6 8. Nxe5 Qh4 {is an interesting pawn sac.}) 7. d3 (7. hxg4 hxg4 {
is simply bad for White.}) 7... Qf6 8. Be3 (8. Nbd2 {is the most common option,
which often allows Black to have more fun.}) 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 Qxf3 10. gxf3 {
is an endgame that should be fine for Black, but often it is difficult to play
since there aren't many dynamic ideas. If White gets in f4 at any point
unhindered, it is usually bad news, so Black needs to always keep an eye on
breaks.}) (5... Qd6 {is a sharp line, and White usually plays aggressively
after} 6. Na3 Be6 7. Qe2 {going for a quick d4 and play against Black's queen.}
) (5... Bd6 {looks nice, but} 6. d4 exd4 7. Qxd4 {is quite annoying. This is a
playable line, however, and isn't particularly explored.}) 6. d4 exd4 (6... Bg4
{is another options, which can lead to more dynamic play.} 7. dxe5 (7. c3 Bd6 {
leads to sharper play.}) 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 fxe5 {is an unusual pawn structure.
Black's e5 pawn is a clear weakness, but Black also gets excellent development.
} 9. Rd3 Bd6 10. Nbd2 Nf6 11. Nc4 O-O {with concrete play. Unlike in most
exchange lines, Black is ahead in development, although if the game becomes
too simplified White can sometimes use the pawn majority on the kingside.}) 7.
Nxd4 {doesn't keep the queens on, but it forced Black to commit to c5.} (7.
Qxd4 Qxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Nc3 O-O-O 10. Be3 Bd6 {There is no need to play c5,
and the pawn on c6 controls the c3 knight well.} 11. Rfd1 Re8 12. Rd2 {Awkward
move.} (12. f3 f5 {was clearly the fear, but after} 13. Bf2 {I'm sure White is
OK.}) 12... Ne7 13. Nb3 Be6 14. Nc5 Ng6 {Note how Black doesn't fear the
capture on e6 due to dynamic counterplay.} 15. f3 (15. Nxe6 Rxe6 16. Rad1 Ne5 {
and Nc4 is not so easy to counter.} 17. b3 Bb4 18. Bd4) 15... Bf7 16. Nd3 b6
17. Bf2 Rd8 18. Rad1 Rd7 19. b3 Rhd8 20. Nb1 Be6 21. c4 f5 22. c5 fxe4 23. cxd6
exd3 24. Rxd3 c5 25. dxc7 Kxc7 26. Rxd7+ Rxd7 27. Rxd7+ Kxd7 28. Bg3 a5 29. Kf2
b5 30. Nd2 b4 31. Ke2 Kc6 32. Kd1 a4 33. Kc2 a3 34. Nf1 c4 35. Ne3 cxb3+ 36.
axb3 Nf8 37. Be5 g6 38. Bg7 Nd7 39. Nf1 Nc5 40. Nd2 h5 41. Bf8 Kd5 42. h3 Bf5+
43. Kc1 Nd3+ 44. Kb1 Kd4 45. g4 Be6 46. Kc2 Ne1+ 47. Kb1 Nd3 48. Kc2 h4 49.
Bg7+ Ke3 50. Bh6+ Ke2 51. Kb1 Nf2 52. Nc4 Nxh3 53. Ne5 g5 54. Nc6 Bd5 55. Nxb4
Bxb3 56. Nc6 Ke3 57. Ne5 Kf4 58. Ng6+ Kg3 {Nakamura-Ivanchuk}) 7... c5 8. Nb3 (
8. Ne2 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bd7 {It is important to allow castling.} 10. Nbc3 O-O-O 11.
Be3 (11. Bf4 g5 {This active idea has merit.} (11... Ne7 {is also fine.}) 12.
Bg3 Ne7 13. f3 Bg7 {[%cal Gf6f5] Black is aiming for f5, and has great play.})
11... Re8 12. Rd2 Bc6 13. Rad1 {White will often delay f3 to discourage f5.} b6
14. a4 Ne7 (14... a5 {is possible, but giving White Nb5 options isn't ideal.})
15. a5 {This looks counterintuitive, "fixing" Black's pawns, but White needs
to play dynamically to use the development edge.} Kb7 16. axb6 (16. Rd8 Rxd8
17. Rxd8 Ng6 {and Black is OK}) 16... cxb6 17. f3 f5 {Black tries to secure
counterplay by creating a weakness.} 18. Rd8 Rxd8 19. Rxd8 Kc7 20. Rd1 fxe4 21.
fxe4 Ng6 22. Nf4 Be7 23. Ncd5+ Bxd5 24. Nxd5+ Kc6 25. Nxe7+ Nxe7 26. Bf4 Ng6
27. Rd6+ Kb5 {Black's active king helps provide counterplay.} 28. Bg5 Re8 29.
Bd8 Rxe4 (29... Kc4 30. Bxb6 Rxe4) 30. Rxb6+ Kc4 31. Kf2 Rd4 32. Bg5 Rd5 33.
Be3 Ne5 34. h3 a5 35. Re6 h5 36. Ke2 a4 37. Bd2 Kb5 38. Bc3 Nc4 39. Rg6 a3 40.
b3 Nb2 41. Rxg7 Rd1 42. Ra7 Rc1 43. Kd2 Rd1+ 44. Ke3 Rc1 45. Kd2 Rd1+ 46. Ke2
Rc1 47. Ra5+ Kb6 48. Kd2 Rd1+ 49. Ke2 Rg1 50. Kf3 Rf1+ 51. Ke2 Rg1 52. Kf3 Rf1+
{1/2-1/2 (52) Guseinov,G (2664)-Onischuk,A (2647) Astana KAZ 2019}) 8... Qxd1
9. Rxd1 Bg4 {provoking the pawn on f3 assists Black tactically.} (9... Be6 {
is playable, but after} 10. Bf4 c4 11. Nd4 O-O-O 12. Nc3 Bf7 13. Nf5 {it is
harder to finish development harmoniously.}) 10. f3 Be6 {The idea of c4 will
alow Black to castle.} 11. Nc3 (11. Be3 b6 {will likely transpose.}) (11. Bf4
c4 12. Nd4 O-O-O 13. Nc3 Bf7 (13... Bc5 {is also playable here, but it is
unclear you want to trade bishops after Be3-Nf5.}) 14. Nf5 Rxd1+ {This feels
counterintuitive, but Black will be able to force White back.} 15. Rxd1 g6 16.
Ne3 Bc5 {followed by Ne7 with easy play.}) 11... Bd6 12. Be3 b6 13. a4 {
This idea is quite common. White has to create weaknesses quickly, as the
kingside majority is tough to realize and Black will have great play once
development is completed.} O-O-O (13... a5 {is playable, but you have to be
cautious allowing Nb5.} 14. Nb5 O-O-O 15. Nxd6+ cxd6 16. Nd2 {Black to Move} d5
(16... Ne7 17. c4 f5 {and Black should be fine.}) 17. exd5 Bxd5 18. b4 $1 (18.
Re1 {also looks annoying, since the g8 knight can't be developed immediately.})
18... axb4 19. a5 {Black is not prepared for dynamic play.} bxa5 20. Bxc5 Nh6
21. Rxa5 Rhe8 22. Bb6 Rd6 23. Nc4 Bxc4 24. Rxd6 Re1+ 25. Kf2 Re2+ 26. Kg3 {
1-0 (26) Mamedyarov,S (2735)-Ragger,M (2688) Vienna AUT 2015}) (13... Kf7 {
is also a move, with the idea of} 14. a5 c4 15. Nd4 b5) 14. a5 {Black to Play}
Bxb3 (14... Kb7 15. e5 $1 fxe5 16. axb6 cxb6 17. Ne4 {and Black has tactical
issues.} Be7 18. Rxd8 Bxd8 19. Nbxc5+ bxc5 20. Nxc5+) 15. cxb3 b5 16. Nd5 Ne7 {
This should allow Black to equalize.} 17. Rac1 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Be5 19. Rcxc5 {
1/2-1/2 (19) Nisipeanu,L (2684)-Onischuk,A (2664) Foros 2008} (19. Rdxc5 Rd3)
19... Rxd5 20. Rxd5 (20. exd5 Rd8) 20... Bxb2 *

